Udacity Nanodegree Capstone Project¶

Predicting ICU mortality based on MIMIC-III database¶

This is the capstone project for Udacity's machine learning project. I am in terested to find out whether patient mortality could be better predicted using different medical record data instead of solely relying on severity scores such as SAPS, etc, which used logistic regression. As a binary classification problem, we have a lot of options in machine learning algorithms. In this project, I intended to test other machine learning algorithms, such as support vector machine and random forest, optimize their performance by tuning hyperparameters,and come up with predictive models with better accuracy for ICU mortality.

The MIMIC-III is a free database, which contains over 60,000 hospital admission data for ICU patients. Medical information was aggregated from many different sources, e.g., hospital admission, ICU charted information, laboratory analysis reports, etc. Therefore, there exist many tables that documents relevant medical history about admitted patients, including lab analysis records, and charted data in ICU care. Without a background in medicine and ICU care, it is a challenge to make sense of the sophisticated data library. To make sense of the what the data actually represent, relevant literatures were collected and read by the author. To be able to gather information important to mortality prediction, structured query language (sql) scripts were first run to compile the libraries from downloaded csv files. Based on selection criteria, new sql script was written to extract necessary information for this project. The sql script was written for postgresql database and is attached to the project report.

Section 1. Data extraction and cleansing¶

In this section, I am going to establish connection with mimiciii database on my local computer and return a table that contains all the medical record information from a query. The master data table was extracted from the mimiciii database using a sql script that I wrote, which pulled relevant medical information and aggregate some of the data from multiple tables in the mimiciii database. I then use pandas dataframe to store the extract the medical information, which satisfy my screening criteria.

The summary statistics tells me something more about the dataset that I am going to work with. There is about 56% of the patients are males. 86% of admissions are emergency. Of all included entries, about 12% of patients died in hospital. Average ICU stay is 4 days and average hospital stay is 11 days. A couple variables contains few entries ('carboxyhemoglobin','o2flow','tidalvolume') or have null values throughout ('ventilationrate'). Therefore, it is decided to drop those columns. Also, it was noted in the published paper on MIMICIII that patient age was intentionally offset to 300 for those aged 89 and older (total 2638 patients). I felt the older patient is valuable information, and thus decided to retain those patients in the dataset. There is only a fraction of those patients, thus, they were given a random age between 89-99[1].

[1]Johnson AE, Pollard TJ, Shen L, Lehman LW, Feng M, Ghassemi M, Moody B, Szolovits P, Celi LA, Mark RG. MIMIC-III, a freely accessible critical care database. Scientific Data. 2016;3.

Further cleansing by attempting to remove seemingly outliers in the feature space It still does not feels right by looking at the mean, standard deviation, and max values for each feature. For example, age has values of 300, which was artificially set to protect patient privacy for those who are 89 years and older. I have taken care of the age feature by swapping the 300 with a random number between 89 and 99. For some other features such as hospital_los, pt, wbc, etc. also showed long tails into larger numbers beyond valid values. Without any solid knowledge about what went into those numbers when they were recorded. It is better off to rely on some other methods to detect and remove outlying data points. First of all, I would like to visualize the distribution of those features, which may help discover things that are not easily detected by simply going through the summary statistics.

Therefore,based on data distribution, it may make sense to apply the IQR rule to remove those outliers for all the numeric features. Because all the features have highly skewed distribution, it more likely to follow the log-normal distribution. if not taking the log, significant number of data points were excluded (~30000). Thus, natural log transform was applied before the IQR rule. Still, some of the features ,such as chloride, led to significant number of exclusion (~20000). Thus, outlier detection in this case should proceed with extreme caution, preferably with expert knowledge regarding what is normal and what is unreasonable. Without proper background in medical science, it is difficult for the author to judge what should be considered normal. In a published study based on MIMICIII, it was also proven that the extreme values for some of the features are actually quite helpful in predicting patient outcomes, thus they contain valuable information that should not be discard. Thus, outlier removal was only attempted on a rather limited subset of features, resulting in roughly ~3400 data points being excluded.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df=pd.read_csv('fillna.csv')

def outlier_removal(df,feature):
    df_log=np.log(df[feature])
    Q1,Q3 =np.percentile(df_log,[25,75])
    iqr=Q3-Q1
    lower=Q1-1.5*iqr
    upper=Q3+1.5*iqr
    outlier=df[(df_log<lower)|(df_log>upper)]
    # print(feature,outlier.count())
    return outlier.index

index_buffer=[]
outlier_index=[]
df_out=df.drop(['icustay_id','emergency_admission','heartrate','hospital_expire_flag','age','icu_los','bands','albumin','chloride','totalco2','spo2','magnesium','calcium','aniongap','bicarbonate','bilirubin','platelet','creatinine','potassium','lactate','inr','pt','sodium','wbc','tempc','glucose','ptt','hemoglobin','hematocrit','resprate','saps','sapsii'],axis=1)
for feature in df_out.keys():
    index=outlier_removal(df_out,feature)
    index_buffer=index_buffer+list(index)
    
outlier_index=list(set(index_buffer))
clean_df=df.drop(outlier_index)
clean_df.to_csv('clean_data.csv')
print(round(clean_df['hospital_expire_flag'].mean(),3))
